This assignment is focused on generating features from numeric inputs for linear models. You will get extensive practice deriving linear, non-linear, additive, and interaction features using the formula interface with dmatrices() and statsmodels. It involves many repetitive and tedious tasks. That is by design! One of the goals of the assignment is for you to see how similar many of the actions are, even when the data change across applications!

You will work with one synthetic data set created specifically for this assignment, as well as a real data set. The synthetic data set gives you experience generating features, fitting models, and interpreting the models through coefficients and predictions. The synthetic data set consists of a single numeric input which simplifies visualization and interpretation. The real data set involves multiple inputs and requires you to develop preprocessing pipelines before generating the features from the inputs.

You are required to create specific features for each problem. Although you fit multiple models, this assignment does not deal with identifying the best model. That topic is reserved for a later assignment. Because this assignment is focused on features you will only fit and interpret models for the synthetic data set in this assignment. Fitting models for the real data set are reserved for later assignments.

You may add as many code and markdown cells as you see fit to answer the questions.

3a)¶

However, before fitting the models. Let's define a function to help interpret the coefficients. The lecture examples defined a function, my_coefplot(), that created a coefficient plot for a statsmodels fit model.

You must define the my_coefplot() function in the cell below. You will use it for the remainder of the assignment.

NOTE: This should not be the my_coefplot_b() function which allows removing the Intercept from the figure.

3a) - SOLUTION¶

In [24]:
def my_coefplot(mod, figsize_use=(10,4)):
    fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=figsize_use)
    ax.errorbar(y=mod.params.index,
                x=mod.params,
                xerr = 2*mod.bse,
                fmt='o', color='k',ecolor='k', elinewidth=2, ms=10)
    ax.axvline(x=0, linestyle='--', color='grey',linewidth=3.5)
    ax.set_xlabel('coefficient value')
    plt.show()

Problem 06¶

Hopefully you noticed that the inputs for this application require some level of preprocessing. Based on your visual exploration, you might be wondering if certain preprocessing actions, such as removing skew, are required. Or, perhaps you not sure how to know if the skew should be removed. When facing such a dilemma, the best approach is to try mutliple approaches! Therefore, you should not make a choice upfront and just stick with it. Instead, you should identify several possible approaches, apply them, and then quantify their differences at the end. We have not discussed yet how to quantify the model performance in CMPINF 2120 (though we did do so in CMPINF 2100). Therefore, this problem is focused on applying the preprocessing rather than ultimately assessing the performance. You will do that in a later assignment.

For this problem though, you will specifically execute two preprocessing pipelines. The first approach standardizes the inputs to remove magnitude and scale effects but does not remove skew. The second approach standardizes, applyes the Quantile transformer, and standardizes again in attempt to remove the skew and make sure all preprocessed inputs have the same magnitude scale.

You will use the Pipeline() function to manage the preprocessing pipelines. You do not need to use ColumnTransformer(). This problem therefore relies on programming skills from the previous assignments.
